```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class EnumInputExample {

    public enum Day {
        MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY, THURSDAY, FRIDAY, SATURDAY, SUNDAY
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.println("Enter a day of the week: ");
        String input = scanner.nextLine().toUpperCase(); // Convert input to uppercase for case-insensitive comparison

        try {
            Day day = Day.valueOf(input);
            System.out.println("You entered: " + day);
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Invalid day entered");
        }

        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

In this example, we take user input for a day of the week and convert it to uppercase using the `toUpperCase()` method to make it case-insensitive. We then use the `Day.valueOf()` method to convert the input string to the corresponding `Day` enum value. If the input does not match any of the enum constants, an `IllegalArgumentException` is caught and "Invalid day entered" is printed.

Certainly! Here are some examples of using enums in Java:

1. Basic enum example:

```java
public class EnumExample {

    enum Day {
        MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY, THURSDAY, FRIDAY, SATURDAY, SUNDAY
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Day today = Day.MONDAY;
        System.out.println("Today is: " + today);
    }
}
```

2. Enums with fields and methods:

```java
public class EnumWithMethods {

    enum Weekday {
        MONDAY("Start of the week"), TUESDAY("Second day"), WEDNESDAY("Middle day"),
        THURSDAY("Almost there"), FRIDAY("Weekend is near");

        private String description;

        Weekday(String desc) {
            this.description = desc;
        }

        public String getDescription() {
            return description;
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Weekday today = Weekday.WEDNESDAY;
        System.out.println("Today is " + today + ": " + today.getDescription());
    }
}
```

3. Using enums with switch-case:

```java
public class EnumWithSwitch {

    enum Fruit {
        APPLE, BANANA, ORANGE, MANGO, GRAPES
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Fruit favoriteFruit = Fruit.BANANA;

        switch (favoriteFruit) {
            case APPLE:
                System.out.println("An apple a day keeps the doctor away");
                break;
            case BANANA:
                System.out.println("I love bananas");
                break;
            case ORANGE:
                System.out.println("Oranges are packed with Vitamin C");
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("I like all fruits");
        }
    }
}
``` 

These examples demonstrate the use of enums in Java, from basic enum declarations to enums with fields, methods, and switch-case statements. Enums are a useful feature for representing fixed sets of constants in a structured and type-safe manner.

